[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Chromium is a free and open-source software project.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Owing to its origins in the WebKit project, Chromium incorporates code subject to a variety of licenses, including LGPL, MIT, Ms-PL, and MPL (with the MPL/GPL/LGPL tri-license clause).
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Original Google-authored portions and some portions written by Apple are shared under the 3-clause BSD license.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] This licensing permits any party to build the codebase and share the resulting browser executable with the Chromium name and logo.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Thus many Linux distributions do this, as well as FreeBSD and OpenBSD.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Chromium also forms the basis of Electron, which in turn is used for many commercial and proprietary cross-platform applications, such as Slack.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Many Chromium-based browsers, such as Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge, include the proprietary components, such as proprietary wrapper libraries for hardware acceleration.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Chromium provides the vast majority of source code for Google Chrome, but there are important differences.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google first chose the name "Chrome" with intention to minimize *chrome* for its browser.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Then the open-source release was named "Chromium" because chromium metal is used to make chrome plating.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Chrome has the same user interface functionality as Chromium, but with a Google-branded color scheme.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Unlike Chromium, Chrome is not open-source; its binaries are licensed as freeware under the Google Chrome Terms of Service.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium browser codebase contains over 36 million source lines of code, excluding comments and blank lines.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Chromium has been a Google project since its inception, and Google employees have done the bulk of the development work.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google refers to this project and the offshoot ChromiumOS as "the Chromium projects", and its employees use @chromium.org email addresses for this development work.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] However, in terms of governance, the Chromium projects are not independent entities; Google retains firm control of them.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium browser codebase is widely used, so others have made important contributions, most notably Microsoft, Avast, Igalia, Yandex, Intel, Samsung, LG, Opera, Vivaldi, and Brave.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Some employees of these companies also have @chromium.org email addresses.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google designed the first multi-process browser.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Compared to single-process designs, this architecture has better responsiveness with many browser tabs open and security benefits of process isolation, but with the trade-off of higher memory usage.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] This was later refined as per-process website isolation, providing additional security.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Another important design decision was for the browser's user interface to be minimalistic.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The browser engine was originally based on Apple's WebKit, which Google deemed the "obvious choice" of available options.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] However, Google's novel multi-process design required engine changes.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] This divergence from Apple's version increased over time, so in 2013 Google officially forked its version as the Blink engine.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] However, as of 2025, Google is still working on getting the Blink engine onto iOS, and has released experimental code for it.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] C++ is the primary language, comprising over half of the codebase.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] This includes the Blink and V8 engines, the implementation of HTTP and other protocols, the internal caching system, the extension API, and most of the user interface.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The rest of the user interface, called the WebUI, is implemented in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript (usually via TypeScript transpilation).
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] An extensive collection of web platform tests is also written in these languages plus XML.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Third-party libraries that provide essential functionality, such as SQLite and numerous codecs, are written in C, C++, or beginning in 2023, the newer Rust language.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Support for mobile operating systems requires special languages: for Android both Java and Kotlin, and for iOS both Objective-C and Swift.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Python is the main language of the build system, which also has special configuration files for Google's GN tool.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The bug tracking system is a publicly accessible website.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Participants are identified by their email addresses.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The Chromium continuous integration system automatically builds and tests the codebase several times a day.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Builds are identified by a four-part version number that is major.minor.build.patch.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] This versioning scheme and the branch points that occur every six to seven weeks are from Google Chrome and its development cycle.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google Chrome debuted in September 2008, and along with its release, the Chromium source code was also made available, allowing builds to be constructed from it.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Upon release, Chrome was criticized for storing a user's passwords without the protection of a master password.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google has insisted that a master password provides no real security against knowledgeable hackers, but users argued that it would protect against co-workers or family members borrowing a computer and being able to view stored passwords as plaintext.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Kasting stated: "A master password was issue 1397.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] We will not implement a master password.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] 'A bunch of people would like it' won't make it happen.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Our design decisions are not democratic.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 3 was the first alpha available for Linux.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Chromium soon incorporated native theming for Linux, using the GTK+ toolkit to allow it fit into the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 3 also introduced JavaScript engine optimizations and user-selectable themes.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 6 introduced features for user interface minimalism, as one of Google's goals was to make the browser "feel lightweight (cognitively and physically) and fast".
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The changes were a unified tools menu, no home button by default (although user configurable), a combined reload/stop button, and the bookmark bar deactivated by default.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] It also introduced an integrated PDF reader, WebM and VP8 support for use with HTML video, and a smarter URL bar.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 7 boosted performance to twice that of prior versions via hardware acceleration.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 8 focused on improved integration into ChromeOS and improved cloud features.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] These include background web applications, host remoting (allowing users centrally to control features and settings on other computers) and cloud printing.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 9 introduced a number of features, including a URL bar feature for exposing phishing attacks and sandboxing for the Adobe Flash plug-in.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Other additions were the WebGL library and access for the new Chrome Web Store.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] In February, Google announced that it was considering large-scale user interface (UI) changes, including at least partial elimination of the URL bar, which had been a mainstay of browsers since the early years of the Web.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The proposed UI was to be a consolidation of the row of tabs and the row of navigation buttons, the menu, and URL bar into a single row.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The justification was freeing up more screen space for web page content.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google acknowledged that this would result in URLs not always being visible to the user, that navigation controls and menus may lose their context, and that the resulting single line could be quite crowded.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] However, by August, Google decided that these changes were too risky and shelved the idea.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] In March, Google announced other directions for the project.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Development priorities focused on reducing the size of the executable, integrating web applications and plug-ins, cloud computing, and touch interface support.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Thus a multi-profile button was introduced to the UI, allowing users to log into multiple Google and other accounts in the same browser instance.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Other additions were malware detection and support for hardware-accelerated CSS transforms.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] By May, the results of Google's attempts to reduce the file size of Chromium were already being noted.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Much of the early work in this area concentrated on shrinking the size of WebKit, the image resizer, and the Android build system.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Subsequent work introduced a more compact mobile version that reduced the vertical space of the UI.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Other changes in 2011 were GPU acceleration on all pages, adding support for the new Web Audio API, and the Google Native Client (NaCl) which permits native code supplied by third parties as platform-neutral binaries to be securely executed within the browser itself.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Google's Skia graphics library was also made available for all Chromium versions.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The sync service added for Google Chrome in 2012 could also be used by Chromium builds.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The same year, a new API for high-quality video and audio communication was added, enabling web applications to access the user's webcam and microphone after asking permission to do so.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Then GPU accelerated video decoding for Windows and support for the QUIC protocol were added.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] In 2013, Chromium's modified WebKit rendering engine was officially forked as the Blink engine.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Other changes in 2013 were the ability to reset user profiles and new browser extension APIs.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Tab indicators for audio and webcam usage were also added, as was automatic blocking of files detected as malware.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Version 67 added the security benefit of per-process website isolation.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Then version 69 introduced a new browser theme, as part of the tenth anniversary of Google Chrome.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] The same year, new measures were added to curtail abusive advertising.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Since 2021, the Google Chrome sync service can no longer be used by Chromium builds.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Also, starting with version 89, only Intel and AMD processors with the SSE3 instruction set or later are supported.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Starting with version 110, only Windows 10 and later are supported for Windows users.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] In addition to Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Opera, Vivaldi and Brave, many other actively developed browsers are based on the Chromium code.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Most of these are proprietary, like Chrome, but some remain free and open-source software (FOSS), like Chromium.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] With either approach, the custom app is implemented with HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and other web technologies.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Moreover, the app can be readily deployed on the operating systems supported by Chromium.
[src:electron-framework/chromium-web-browser] Since the 2010s, many apps have been created this way.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Electron was originally built for Atom and is the main GUI framework behind several other open-source projects including GitHub Desktop, Light Table, WordPress Desktop, and Eclipse Theia.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] It is also used in Microsoft's proprietary code editor Visual Studio Code.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Chromium forms the basis of a managed runtime, allowing application developers to write cross-platform applications in memory-safe JavaScript or TypeScript and target Web browser technologies including HTML, CSS, and SVG for graphics.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Electron-based applications include a "main" process and several "renderer" processes.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] The main process runs the logic for the application (e.g., menus, shell commands, lifecycle events), and can then launch multiple renderer processes by instantiating an instance of the `BrowserWindow` class, which loads a window that appears on the screen to render HTML, CSS, etc.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Both the main and renderer processes can run with Node.js integration if the `nodeIntegration` field in the main process is set to `true`.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Most of Electron's APIs are written in C++ or Objective-C and are exposed directly to the application code through JavaScript bindings.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Electron frequently releases new major versions along every other Chromium release.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] The latest three stable versions are supported by the Electron team.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Desktop applications built with Electron include Atom, balenaEtcher, Discord, Slack, and Visual Studio Code.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] The Brave browser was based on Electron before it was rewritten to use Chromium directly, while Microsoft Teams used Electron before 2.0.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] The most common criticism of Electron is that it necessitates software bloat when used for simple programs.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] As a result, Michael Larabel has referred to the framework as "notorious among most Linux desktop users for being resource heavy, not integrating well with most desktops, and generally being despised".
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Researchers have shown that Electron's large feature set can be hijacked by bad actors with write access to the source JavaScript files.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] This requires root access on Unix-like systems and is not considered to be a vulnerability by the Electron developers.
[src:electron-framework/electron-software-framework] Those who are concerned that Electron is not always based on the newest version of Chromium have recommended progressive web applications as an alternative.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] In computer science, **interprocess communication** (**IPC**) is the sharing of data between running processes in a computer system, or between multiple such systems.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Mechanisms for IPC may be provided by an operating system.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Applications which use IPC are often categorized as clients and servers, where the client requests data and the server responds to client requests.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Many applications are both clients and servers, as commonly seen in distributed computing.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] IPC is very important to the design process for microkernels and nanokernels, which reduce the number of functionalities provided by the kernel.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Those functionalities are then obtained by communicating with servers via IPC, leading to a large increase in communication when compared to a regular monolithic kernel.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] IPC interfaces generally encompass variable analytic framework structures.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] These processes ensure compatibility between the multi-vector protocols upon which IPC models rely.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] An IPC mechanism is either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Synchronization primitives may be used to have synchronous behavior with an asynchronous IPC mechanism.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Merging data from two processes can often incur significantly higher costs compared to processing the same data on a single thread, potentially by two or more orders of magnitude due to overheads such as inter-process communication and synchronization.
[src:electron-framework/inter-process-communication] Different approaches to IPC have been tailored to different software requirements, such as performance, modularity, and system circumstances such as network bandwidth and latency.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:electron-framework/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Google created V8 for its Chrome browser, so V8's first release coincided with Chrome's first release in 2008.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] It was named after the V8 engine, and its lead developer was Lars Bak.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] For several years, Chrome was faster than other browsers at executing JavaScript.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] The V8 assembler is based on the Strongtalk assembler.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] On 7 December 2010, a new compiling infrastructure named Crankshaft was released, with speed improvements.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] In version 41 of Chrome in 2015, project TurboFan was added to provide more performance improvements with previously challenging workloads such as asm.js.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Much of V8's development is strongly inspired by the Java HotSpot Virtual Machine developed by Sun Microsystems, with the newer execution pipelines being very similar to those of HotSpot's.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Support for the WebAssembly language began in 2015.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] In 2016, the Ignition interpreter was added to V8 with the design goal of reducing the memory usage on small memory Android phones in comparison with TurboFan and Crankshaft.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Ignition is a register based machine and shares a similar (albeit not the exact same) design to the templating interpreter utilized by HotSpot.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] In 2017, V8 shipped a brand-new compiler pipeline, consisting of Ignition (the interpreter) and TurboFan (the optimizing compiler).
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Starting with V8 version 5.9, Full-codegen (the early baseline compiler) and Crankshaft are no longer used in V8 for JavaScript execution, since the team believed they were no longer able to keep pace with new JavaScript language features and the optimizations those features required.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] In 2021, a new tiered compilation pipeline was introduced with the release of the SparkPlug compiler, which supplements the existing TurboFan compiler within V8, in a direct parallel to the profiling C1 Compiler used by HotSpot.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] V8 first generates an abstract syntax tree with its own parser.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Then, Ignition generates bytecode from this syntax tree using the internal V8 bytecode format.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] TurboFan compiles this bytecode into machine code.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] In other words, V8 compiles ECMAScript directly to native machine code using just-in-time compilation before executing it.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] The compiled code is additionally optimized (and re-optimized) dynamically at runtime, based on heuristics of the code's execution profile.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] Optimization techniques used include inlining, elision of expensive runtime properties, and inline caching.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] The garbage collector is a generational incremental collector.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] V8 can compile to x86, ARM or MIPS instruction set architectures in both their 32-bit and 64-bit editions; it has additionally been ported to PowerPC, and to IBM ESA/390 and z/Architecture, for use in servers.
[src:electron-framework/v8-javascript-engine] V8 can be used in a browser or integrated into independent projects.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code is proprietary software released under the "Microsoft Software License", but based on the MIT licensed program named "Visual Studio Code – Open Source" (also known as "Code – OSS"), also created by Microsoft and available through GitHub.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, out of over 49,000 responses, 75.9% of respondents reported using Visual Studio Code, more than twice the percentage of respondents who reported using its nearest alternative, Visual Studio.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code was first announced on April 29, 2015, by Microsoft at the 2015 Build conference.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] A preview build was released shortly thereafter.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] On November 18, 2015, the project "Visual Studio Code – Open Source" (also known as "Code – OSS"), on which Visual Studio Code is based, was released under the open-source MIT License and made available on GitHub.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] On April 14, 2016, Visual Studio Code graduated from the public preview stage and was released to the web.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code includes a source-code editor that can be used with a variety of programming languages, including C, C#, C++, Fortran, Go, Java, JavaScript, Node.js, Python, Rust, and Julia.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code employs the same editor component (codenamed "Monaco") used in Azure DevOps (formerly called "Visual Studio Online" and "Visual Studio Team Services").
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] The downloadable version of Visual Studio Code is built on the Electron framework, which is used to develop Node.js web applications that run on the Blink layout engine.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code for the Web is a browser-based version of the editor that can be used to edit both local files and remote repositories (on GitHub and Microsoft Azure) without installing the full program.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It is officially supported and hosted by Microsoft and can be accessed at vscode.dev.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Out of the box, Visual Studio Code includes basic support for most common programming languages.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This basic support includes syntax highlighting, bracket matching, code folding, and configurable snippets.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code also ships with IntelliSense for JavaScript, TypeScript, JSON, CSS, and HTML, as well as debugging support for Node.js.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Support for additional languages can be provided by freely available extensions on the VS Code Marketplace.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] VS Code features a built-in debugger designed to enhance the development process.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It provides native support for debugging Node.js applications, while additional debuggers for other programming languages can be installed via extensions.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] The debugger allows developers to attach to running processes and step through source code line-by-line during execution, offering a detailed view of program flow.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It can also display disassembly for low-level analysis in C++.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Furthermore, users can set breakpoints – either standard or conditional – to pause execution at specific points and examine the program's state, while also monitoring variable values in real-time as the code runs.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] An interactive feature of VS Code's debugging toolkit is the Debug Console.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This panel is integrated directly into the debugging session, enabling users to evaluate expressions, such as checking variable values or testing functions, and execute commands on the fly.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This functionality provides developers with greater control and deeper insight into the program's behavior.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Instead of a project system, VS Code allows users to open one or more directories, which can then be saved in workspaces for future reuse.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This allows it to operate as a language-agnostic code editor for any language.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It supports many programming languages and a set of features that differ per language.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Unwanted files and folders can be excluded from the project tree via settings.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Many Visual Studio Code features are not exposed through menus or the user interface but can be accessed via the Command Palette.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] The Command Palette is able to execute virtually every feature the graphical interface supports, making it very keyboard-accessible.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code provides a fully featured *integrated terminal* that opens at the root of the current workspace, allowing users to run shell commands without leaving the editor environment.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It can be toggled via **View → Terminal**, the Command Palette (`View: Toggle Integrated Terminal`), or the keyboard shortcut (`Ctrl+'`).
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Users may open multiple terminals in tabs or split panes, rename them, and kill sessions individually, directly within the editor UI.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This terminal hosts any shell installed on the system—Bash, Zsh, PowerShell, Fish, Git Bash, WSL, etc.—and detects available profiles automatically, making it simple to switch contexts via the dropdown menu or the `Terminal: Select Default Profile` command.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Beyond basic command execution, VS Code's shell integration also contains clickable file links, working directory awareness, and error-detection markers in the scrollbar.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] These enhancements simplify tracing errors and navigating code paths by allowing direct jumps to source files, preserving the current working directory context, and highlighting problems inline within the terminal's scroll bar.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code can be extended via extensions.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Users may install extensions from the VS Code Marketplace to add language support, editor, themes, debuggers, and additional utilities.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] A notable feature is the ability to create extensions that add support for new languages, themes, debuggers, time travel debuggers, perform static code analysis, and add code linters using the Language Server Protocol.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Source control is a built-in feature of Visual Studio Code.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It has a dedicated tab inside the menu bar where users can access version control settings and view changes made to the current project.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] To use the feature, Visual Studio Code must be linked to any supported version control system (Git, Apache Subversion, Perforce, etc.).
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This allows users to create repositories and to make push and pull requests directly from the Visual Studio Code program.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code collects usage data and sends it to Microsoft to help improve the product.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] The information contained in this telemetry data can be inspected by the public, since the product is open source.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] VS Code supports remote development through extensions such as Remote–SSH, Remote–Containers, and Remote–WSL.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] These tools enable users to connect to and develop within remote environments, including servers and containers.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Visual Studio Code for the Web (accessible at vscode.dev) allows users to edit files directly in a web browser without the need to install the desktop application.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This version supports basic editing tasks and integration with remote repositories.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] VS Code Insiders is a nightly build version of this code editor, providing users with the opportunity to experience new features, bug fixes, and improvements ahead of their official release.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] It is compiled every night based on the latest changes from the development team, allowing users to test and provide feedback before these updates are officially released in the stable version.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This version is completely independent of the standard version, meaning users can install and run both simultaneously without any interference between their settings, extensions, or themes.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] This design enables developers to explore and experiment with the latest features of the code editor without affecting their primary development environment.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] In the 2016 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, Visual Studio Code ranked 13th among the top popular development tools, with only 7% of the 47,000 respondents using it.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Two years later, Visual Studio Code rose to the no.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] 1 spot, with 35% of the 75,000 respondents using it.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] Since then Visual Studio Code has retained the no.
[src:electron-framework/visual-studio-code] The 2020 Developers Survey did not cover integrated development environments.
